  ${C_CYAN}destroy${C_RESET} [name|uuid]         Delete a RAID set (data loss - confirms twice).

  ${C_BOLD}-- Health monitoring (designed for launchd) --${C_RESET}
  ${C_CYAN}health${C_RESET} [--dry-run|--once|-v]
                              Run one monitoring pass. Checks RAID set
                              state on every call. Runs SMART checks
                              once per SMART_POLL_INTERVAL_SEC (default:
                              daily). On new/ongoing problems: plays
                              alarm (rate-limited by ALARM_INTERVAL_SEC),
                              sends email (rate-limited by
                              EMAIL_INTERVAL_SEC), and logs.
                                --dry-run  perform checks, no alerts
                                --once     bypass rate limits (testing)
                                -v         debug logging for this run
                              Exit: 0=ok, 1=warn, 2=crit.
  ${C_CYAN}show-config${C_RESET}                 Print effective config values and which
                              config file (if any) was loaded.
  ${C_CYAN}create-config${C_RESET} <path>        Write an annotated default config file to
                              <path>. Example:
                                ${SCRIPT_NAME} create-config ~/.appleRAID.conf
  ${C_CYAN}test-alerts${C_RESET}                 Exercise every alerting channel (sound,
                              email, log). Run once after setup to
                              verify alerts reach you.
  ${C_CYAN}install-daemon${C_RESET}              Generate and load a LaunchDaemon plist.
                              Path/label/interval from config keys
                              LAUNCHD_PLIST, LAUNCHD_LABEL,
                              LAUNCHD_INTERVAL_SEC. Requires sudo.
  ${C_CYAN}uninstall-daemon${C_RESET}            Unload and remove the LaunchDaemon.

  ${C_CYAN}help${C_RESET}, --help, -h            This message.

${C_BOLD}CONFIG FILE SEARCH PATH${C_RESET}
  First readable file wins:
    \$APPLERAID_CONFIG              (env var, for testing)
    /LINKS/default/appleRAID.conf
    ~/.appleRAID.conf
    /usr/local/etc/appleRAID.conf
    /etc/appleRAID.conf
  If none found, built-in defaults are used. 'show-config' will tell you.

${C_BOLD}VERBOSE BY DESIGN${C_RESET}
  Every state-changing command is echoed (with a leading '\$') right
  before being executed, so you can see exactly what is happening.
  Read-only queries (diskutil info, etc.) are mostly silent to reduce
  noise.

${C_BOLD}EXAMPLES${C_RESET}
  ${C_BOLD}-- Management --${C_RESET}
  ${SCRIPT_NAME} list
  ${SCRIPT_NAME} disks
  ${SCRIPT_NAME} wipe 3
  ${SCRIPT_NAME} create BackupGold 2 3
  ${SCRIPT_NAME} repair BackupGold
  ${SCRIPT_NAME} status
  ${SCRIPT_NAME} test BackupGold

  ${C_BOLD}-- Health monitoring setup --${C_RESET}
  # 1. Create and edit a config file
  ${SCRIPT_NAME} create-config /usr/local/etc/appleRAID.conf
  vi /usr/local/etc/appleRAID.conf        # set EMAIL_TO, thresholds, etc.
  ${SCRIPT_NAME} show-config              # verify what will be used
  # 2. Dry-run a health pass (no alerts)
  ${SCRIPT_NAME} health --dry-run -v
  # 3. Verify alerting works end-to-end
  ${SCRIPT_NAME} test-alerts
  # 4. Install the LaunchDaemon (runs every 60s as root)
  sudo ${SCRIPT_NAME} install-daemon
  # 5. Tail the log
  tail -f /var/log/appleRAID.log

${C_BOLD}SAFETY NOTES${C_RESET}
  - This script will run 'sudo' for destructive operations. It will
    prompt for your password the first time and reuse the cached
    credential for the rest of the invocation.
  - Whole-disk operations (wipe, create, repair) require you to type
    the literal word 'yes' to proceed. 'y' is also accepted.
  - Always verify device numbers with '${SCRIPT_NAME} disks' before
    running destructive commands. macOS disk numbers can shift across
    reboots and re-plugs.
EOF
}

